</a> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=booboo>BooBoo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/1/02 12:10:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=883.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: oddities</span><hr size=1> This is how I determine the effectiveness of spell.  I bring it up because to me it seems a much better way of deciding who is better. <br>
<br>
To start with, we'll take a group consisting of a warrior, monk, rogue, shaman, enchanter and a wizard.  Pretend that the warrior has a DPS average of 40, the monk 50 and the rogue 60.  (These numbers were made up just to make the math easier)  Second, pretend the mob does the constant damage of 100 per second.<br>
<br>
In a group, it's not who actually dealt the damage that is given credit for it but the person whose resources we're consumed.<br>
<br>
First example.  The shaman 25% hastens the warrior for 3 minutes.  In this case the shaman brought to the group 1800 damage    (40 damage/second * .25 (the increased damage) * 180 seconds = 1800) Again, spell statistics are made up for ease of calculations. <br>
<br>
Second example.  The wizard stuns the mobs for 6 seconds.  The wizard's spent resources caused 900 damage.  (150 combined DPS from fighters * 6 seconds)<br>
<br>
Third example.  The cleric heals the warrior for 1000 hp.  Since the hp healed effectively nullifies the damage of the mob, heals can be thought of as a stun.  In this case a 10 second stun which in turn allows the party to deal 1500 damage.<br>
<br>
Fourth example.  The shaman slows the mob 50% for 3 minutes.  This affect is the same stunning a mob for 1.5 minutes and having it normal the rest of the time.  (This is not true for caster mobs but we can worry about that has we get more detailed)  So, this slow can follow the stun rules for damage which means the shaman's mana has caused 13500 damage.  Wow that's a lot.  However, in practice this number is rarely so high since a mob rarely lasts 3 minutes.  This does show how a high level shaman with a 70% slow can still solo so well.  It turns his spear poking and pet's biting into a very significant amount of damage.<br>
<br>
Fifth example.  To mobs are pulled.  One is rendered harmless from some type of CC.  (Root or mez or even fear in the right circumstances.)  Since there are 2 mobs, the enemies DPS would be doubles to 200 per second.   CC in this case would be handled like a 50% slow against a 200dps mob.  This example can also fit a good puller splitting mobs.<br>
<br>
So far in all these examples, the fighters are not credited with any damage because none of their resources have been consumed.  To be more precise, you can factor in the tanks regen as a heal to figure out how much damage for which they should get credit.<br>
<br>
Next, we give credit to the tanks.  In order for everyone to get credit the mobs true DPS is the damage that mob does against a necked, defenseless person.  Using the numbers we already have, say this mob does 1000 DPS verses a helpless person but only 100 DPS verses the warrior.  In this case, the presence of the warrior is pretty much a permanent 90% slow.<br>
<br>
I could go on with these examples but this way of thinking, though sometimes a little complex seems fairly intuitive to me.  Just takes a little creativity some times.<br>
<br>
Conclusion<br>
High DPS is important since it makes the affect of the rest of the party higher.  But for true class comparison, straight DPS needs to me factored with the other abilities of that class and with the rest of the party.  Sure, damage per second is important but the enchanters haste and the shamans slows are still very important.  A cleric choosing stuns over heals depends on the DPS of the party and the DPS of the mob.  Also, high DPS is great, but without the support of other classes, pure DPS wont take you very far.<br>
<br>
Finally, this post isn't about class balance.  Wizards, other then their few stuns and limited cc, are damage dealers.  Whether our short term high damage compares to the long-term steady damage of other classes, well you decide.  My fingers hurt from typing.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uikeya.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ikeya</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer<br>Ikeya != Chick</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/1/02 4:38:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=883.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: oddities</span><hr size=1> WIZVAX! Your signature is too long.<br>
